      "Ethics": {
        "title": "Experimental and Social Ethics",
        "contribution": "Dewey rejected fixed moral laws or absolute ends, proposing an experimental, situational ethics centered on growth and adaptation. He viewed ethical inquiry as a process of reflective intelligence applied to concrete moral dilemmas arising in social contexts. Conduct is fundamentally social, shaped by habits and customs, but open to intelligent reconstruction. Values are not discovered but evaluated based on their consequences for ongoing experience and the promotion of growth and harmony within individuals and communities. Democracy was seen as the most ethical way of life, fostering the conditions for individual and social growth through cooperative inquiry and deliberation.",
