        "impact": "Provided a powerful alternative to deontological and utilitarian ethics by focusing on character, habits, context, and consequences for growth. Influenced social ethics, environmental ethics, and theories of moral education. Linked ethics inextricably with social and political life and educational practice."
      },
      "Politics": {
        "title": "Democracy as a Way of Life and Social Inquiry",
        "contribution": "Dewey's political philosophy redefined democracy as more than a form of government; it is fundamentally 'a way of associated living' based on free communication, shared experience, and cooperative inquiry aimed at addressing common problems. He critiqued both atomic individualism and static theories of rights, viewing the 'public' as an instrumental response to the consequences of associated action. He argued that the health of democracy depends on the cultivation of intelligent habits of inquiry, communication, and participation through education. Political problems are seen as requiring experimental, scientific methods of social intelligence to solve, rejecting reliance on dogma or vested interests.",
