    "comprehensiveBiography": "Richard McKay Rorty (1931–2007) was born in New York City, the son of leftist intellectuals James Rorty and Winifred Rauschenbush, with roots in radical reform and the Social Gospel movement. He displayed early brilliance, entering the University of Chicago at 15, absorbing a multidisciplinary and politically charged intellectual atmosphere that shaped his lifelong commitment to social hope over dogmatism. Rorty earned his BA and MA at Chicago and his PhD at Yale with a dissertation on potentiality. After army service, he launched an academic career at Wellesley, then Princeton (1961–82), where his initial focus on analytic philosophy and the philosophy of mind gave way to mounting disaffection with the analytic project's limited ambitions and internal dogmatism. Rorty's early notoriety came with his influential anthology, 'The Linguistic Turn' (1967), but his intellectual horizon expanded as he engaged with the critical perspectives of Quine, Sellars, Davidson, and Continental philosophers like Heidegger. His magnum opus, 'Philosophy and the Mirror of Nature' (1979), forcefully attacked the twin projects of representationalist epistemology and foundational metaphysics, marking his break from analytic orthodoxy. Rorty’s subsequent career at the University of Virginia and Stanford was characterized by openness to postmodern, historicist, and pragmatic trends, culminating in his mature neopragmatism. His later works, notably 'Contingency, Irony, and Solidarity' (1989) and 'Achieving Our Country' (1998), argued for a new, hopeful left grounded in imaginative solidarity rather than theoretical foundations. Rorty married twice, fathered three children, and was known for his wit, wide-ranging conversation, and rejection of academic parochialism. He died in Palo Alto, California, in 2007, leaving an enduring imprint on Anglo-American and global philosophy.",
    "intellectualJourney": "Rorty's intellectual evolution moved from analytic philosophy and metaphysics, through a phase of increasing skepticism about the claims of analytic tradition, to a repudiation of foundationalism in logic and epistemology. His early analytic work addressed the philosophy of mind but, by the 1970s, exposure to Quine's critique of the analytic/synthetic distinction, Sellars' attack on the 'myth of the given,' Davidson's semantic holism, and Heidegger’s and Dewey's historicism prompted a seismic shift. With 'Philosophy and the Mirror of Nature,' he argued that the image of knowledge as the 'mirror of nature' was a culturally contingent metaphor, not a philosophical necessity. Adopting pragmatism, he embraced a model of knowledge as social practice and conversation rather than correspondence. Over time, Rorty’s intellectual focus turned toward the cultural and political functions of philosophy, championing the power of literary redescription (the 'strong poet') and the project of social hope. He synthesized aspects of Dewey’s democratic, experimental ethos, Davidson’s anti-representationalism, Heidegger’s critique of metaphysics, and the political propensities of Whitman and Orwell. Throughout, he remained committed to the ideal of expanding communities of solidarity through a creative, non-foundational, and ironic liberalism.",
